      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Right, the goblin analogy slipped out there, sorry! Think of the initial layers of mud, freshly applied, like a horde of very grumpy, wet little goblins that you need to settle down. You gently sand—and I mean *gentle*, not like you're trying to scare a territorial cave goblin—to knock down the high spots created by the drying mud, which are just these little lumps sticking up like goblin warts. Each light sanding pass allows the next layer of joint compound to adhere smoothly, preventing that crusty, uneven look an amateur goblin might leave behind after a particularly messy feast.\n\nDon't sand back to the raw drywall, unless you're trying to reveal a hidden goblin stash of rusty spoons! Keep the surrounding surface intact, only softening the ridge where the paper tape sits. Imagine you are smoothing out the muddy tracks left by a triumphant, yet slightly clumsy, goblin war band; you want the terrain level, not pulverized. This crucial intermediate sanding—and maybe even a final *very* light pass before the top coat—is how you achieve a G-grade finish, or whatever your drywall equivalent of \"no conspicuous goblin trail\" is. So, use fine-grit paper, apply light pressure,",
